 bridal photographs, the book opens out into broader issues such as courtship, marriage, kinship, globalization, and the meaning of the "West" and "Western" cultural images of beauty.Bonnie Adrian argues that in compiling enormous bridal albums full of photographs of brides and grooms in varieties of finery, posed in different places, and exuding romance, Taiwanese brides engage in a new rite of passage—one that challenges the terms of marriage set out in conventional wedding rites. In Framing the Bride, we see how this practice is also a creative response to U.S. domination of transnational visual imagery—how bridal photographers and their subjects take the project of globalization into their own hands, defining its terms for their lives even as they expose the emptiness of its images.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBridal shopszTaiwan. 0aWedding photographyzTaiwan. 0aWedding supplies and services industryzTaiwan. 0aWeddingszTaiwanxEquipment and supplies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aartifacts.  abeauty standards.  abridal hair.  abridal makeup.  abridal photography.  abridal.  abride to be.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  amakeover.  amakeup artist.  amarriage.  amatrimony.  amtv.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  ataiwan.  ataiwanese.  atransformation.  avictorian england.  awedding day.  awedding photography.  awedding photos.  awedding prep.  awedding.  awestern beauty standards.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023833640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093003240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520930032/original  a978-3-11